flavorTextEntries.flavorText: Capable of outplaying any team with nRated at the helm (EU LCS-high 18 wins) and look to continue that trend in Summer.
Despite an up-and-down Spring Split, Fnatic are dominant in their wins (17.6 pts in victories) and come off valuable All-Star experience.
Suffered major blow with the loss of Mid laner, Alex Ich. However, the rest of the core remains and may be strong enough to be contenders.
Comes off a great win-streak at end of Spring (4th overall pts for teams). If they fix communication issues, expect them to keep winning.
Dominated in their promotion games and, with time to develop their talent, could easily turn into one of EU's top teams.
Have lost a few of their key players to other teams, but have shown resilience before (1st in pts/game during losses in Spring).
Great teamwork in all positions but typically won't destroy any specific match. Strong results may come as other teams test new rosters.
The addition of KottenX into the jungle role has revitalized the roster and appears to have the team ready to challenge the upper echelon.
Fan-favorite can run away simply by winning lanes. New Jungler, Amazing, should continue that trend, but losing Xpecial could be damaging.
Have dramatically improved each Split (18 Wins, 3rd place in Spring), enter Summer featuring Korean import Seraph in Top lane.
Made an aggressive move by acquiring Team Coast's solo laners. With strong foundations in all lanes, have everything prepared to dominate.
Performed extremely well to close out Spring playoffs. A repeat performance combined with acquiring Xpecial should ensure a strong finish.
Poised to defend their back-to-back Split titles on their strong objective control (89 Dragons in Spring, 13 more than 2nd best team).
Showed a lot of promise late in season (21-pt game in Wk 11). More time together should turn this squad into contenders.
Features an all-around roster that has been together since the last promotion. LCS veteran pr0lly is the star to watch.
Considered as one of NA's best challenger teams and features aggressive shotcalling. They have sometimes been sloppy in closing out games.
Is SK Gaming's anchor in the bot lane (only 5 single digit point-performances in Spring). His Summer production should stay consistent.
Won't always dominate games by himself, but rarely has poor performance with his solid farm (2nd in CS for all Top laners).
An adept, supportive Jungler who will rarely make glaring mistakes (51 Assists in final 5 games). A safe and consistent pick-up.
Loves to assassinate enemy carries and exploded late in split (20+ pts in 4 of last 5 games). Early games will show if he can keep it up.
Isn't afraid to try new champions and often makes great calls for SK Gaming. Another split alongside CandyPanda will help boost scores.
Averaged 17.0 pts during Spring Split (3rd best Top laner overall) and will break out new picks. He is reliable on meta champions, too.
Benefits from supporting strong carries in team-fights (6.9 Assists/game in Spring), should be a consistent pick with this roster.
Fnatic rises and falls with their famous captain; guaranteed to have huge games (led EU LCS with 125 Kills) but can be a tad inconsistent.
Every top ADC needs a strong Support, Yellowstar more than fits the role (8.5 Assists/game in Spring). Scores can rise with team success.
ADC prodigy who, even when team is behind, manages to post great scores (2nd fewest Deaths of ADCs, 2nd highest CS). Worthy of a top pick.
Consistently draws the Jungler's attention and still brings immense presence (5th most Assists for Top laners in only 26 games).
A top tier Jungler who can make huge plays in team-fights. He'll need to gel quickly with his new Mid lane to continue making an impact.
A conservative ADC with strong positioning in team-fights capped by a Penta Kill in playoffs (34 Deaths Spring Split, lowest among ADCs).
Support Prince (most Kills, top CS for Support in Spring), can cost his ADC kills. Consider drafting with Genja to avoid "kill stealing."
Will always be relevant due to farm (most CS/game at 310 in Spring for Top laners). Current meta favors his champion pool (Irelia FTW!).
MVP of Spring Split, will farm up huge CS numbers (1st for all Mid laners). Can improve further if Alliance plays to its potential.
Emerged as one of the top Junglers (3rd most Kills, 4th most CS for Junglers in Spring). Will continue to grow with more time on the team.
Has the mechanics to win team-fights and benefits from the heavy focus onto Mid. Trailed only Rekkles and Forgiven in CS last Split.
A quiet Support, but he'll put up the solid numbers to win games. One of the most experienced Supports in EU, should build through split.
Great on tanky champions (best fantasy performances are with Renekton and Mundo). Another split to gain experience will do wonders.
Streaky player with definite champion strengths (Wukong, Vi), success may depend on number of bans directed at him.
Talented carry (9 games with 20+ pts in Spring), should benefit from new support Wewillfailer, who will have stronger lane presence.
Moderate success in Spring Split (13.5 pts/game) across only 8 games, but there is plenty of room to grow as he gains LCS experience.
Won't turn heads by solo carrying games, but his willingness to diversify his champion pool makes him deadly (32.2 pts as Heimer vs. SHC).
Won 2 Week MVP awards and can carry games (2nd in Kills for all Junglers on CW). With Oddone's coaching, he should flourish.
Needs to be more consistent, but will post great numbers when given comfort champs (25 pts as Ziggs against xPeke's Syndra).
Turned in solid (not flashy) performances with Forgiven; will need to quickly build chemistry with Woolite to create fantasy value.
Has huge shoes to fill after Forgiven's departure. With Denial eSports, he played well against CW in Promotions, but LCS will be tougher.
Won't carry games by himself, but he'll handle lane without problems (2nd least Kills, but 2nd least Deaths of all Top laners last split).
A frequent ganker who soaks a lot of farm (most CS for Junglers in Spring Split). Can take advantage this split with EU roster shuffles.
A versatile player who can farm or roam. Not afraid to bring out pocket-picks (like Kayle) to ensure favorable matchup against other Mids.
Won't dominate games by himself, but performs well enough to give his team a chance in any game (only 1.7 Deaths/game last Spring).
The key playmaker in the bot lane and team-fights for ROCCAT (47 total Deaths in Spring, 15 less than next best Support).
A core part of MIL's roster (6th overall Top lane in pts/game). He should gain freedom from enemy Jungler camps with addition of KottenX.
When team wins, he will carry hard (league-leading 28.7 average pts in his team's wins). Should benefit most from KottenX moving forward.
Has the capability to turn in some of the league's best scores (2 games with over 45+ pts). Consistency will be key heading into Summer.
A capable Support who helps keep Creaton on point in the game. Value will rely on Creaton's performance (T-1st in average pts during wins).
Made an immediate impact upon joining the team (17.3 pt average in final 6 Spring games). Expect him to continue that streak into Summer.
The quintessential, consistent Top laner who tied with Balls for least Deaths in Spring, and ranked No. 2 in pts per game for all Tops.
Can take over games (tops in the league for ADCs in Kills and Assists). Must work with new Support, Gleebglarbu, to continue that trend.
Makes huge plays and typically tops the Assists charts (306 total Assists only 7 behind 1st). May struggle early while developing with Cop.
MVP of Spring Split; led all NA/EU players in Kills (155) and only played 22 games. Synergy with Amazing will be important moving forward.
The perennial ADC who can dominate games himself, (3rd overall ADC in Spring). A full split with dexter should see improvements.
A rising star who is able to create advantages throughout the game. Averaged 9.6 Assists per game over Spring and can still improve.
Carries from the jungle (3.7 Kills/game in Spring Split). Expect him to continue if he can build rapport with new Top laner Seraph.
Takes big gambles, but has Deaths rewarded with Kills/Assists (5th most Deaths, but 5th most points as Support in Spring, 13.8 pts/game).
Is the key factor in setting the pace (3rd in Jungler Assists with 200 during Spring). Fantasy production can improve with solid laners.
Shows great results regardless of matchups (5th overall ADC last Spring with 19.0 pts/game). New laners may relieve pressure in bot lane.
Has lost a bit of luster since leaving top lane, but is still a dangerous carry with fantasy star potential (averaged 26.4 pts in CRS wins).
Quietly amasses strong scores with low Deaths and high CS (18.3 pts/game). Addition of Xpecial should help increase Kill totals.
An immovable laner; will hold his own against anyone (1 of 5 Top laners with more Kills than Deaths last split). Consistent, safe pick.
Playmaking improved in Spring (6th in Assists/game for Junglers at 6.5) and can go higher with Xpecial helping out in shotcalling.
Was top 3 in both Kills and Assists for all Top laners in Spring Split. With no roster changes in C9, expect his performance to continue.
His carry-oriented style (most Kills with 107 in Spring, 27 more than 2nd best Jungler), makes him one of Summer's top Jungler picks.
Makes plays for other carries on the team (200 Assists last Split, 52 more than the next best Mid), unlikely to decline in Summer.
Reigning Spring Split KDA leader and only 1 Kill and 2 Assists behind top ADC, WildTurtle. Could be challenged by improved ADCs this Split.
Consistent performer who led the entire LCS last Split with 313 Assists, hit the 10-Assist bonus in 75% of his games.
Versatile and opens up a lot of strategic options. Consistency (20.6 pts/game as Mid) should continue as he and dexter gain experience.
Has a high-risk, high-reward play style (27 assists against CRS Week 5). If EG improves this Summer, look for even bigger rewards.
Known for a supportive play style (6.3 Assists/game last split), his numbers should increase as Innox and Pobelter gain more experience.
Often overshadowed by other two carries on the team; the talent is there (46-pt performance against CRS) but needs to be more consistent.
Major threat with room for growth (9/0/24 in 3 Promotion victories over C9T). If he meets his own high expectations, he will be a star.
Able to play off-meta picks and has carry potential (3rd most Kills for Top laners, only 2 behind 1st). Needs to rein in his 1v1 dueling.
Comes off supporting one of NA Challenger's Top carries in Altec. His adaptability should prove valuable moving over to TSM.
A Challenger grinder with tons of matchup experience to draw upon for his debut. Competition in the LCS should strengthen his game.
Emotional leader and shotcaller who brings LCS experience to the team; can make big plays (led COL's Kills for 3 of 4 games in Promotion).
Has developed into a rising star; might have a rough adjustment but is one of the top carries and can improve (500+ CS in Game 1 vs. CST).
Longtime team veteran has developed great synergy with RobertxLee over the Challenger Series; rarely makes big mistakes that cost his team.
Returns to the NA LCS; brings plenty of surprise picks and possesses strong laning mechanics that allow him to keep up with most Mids.
World Final vet has dominated the Challenger Series using multiple champs and loves to aggressively attack (30+ pts against XDG Game 1).
Noname farms minions and champions, and loves to make aggressive plays (2nd-most Kills on team during Promotion Tournament).
A farm machine, outpacing any of his Challenger opponents by considerable margins (19/1/21, 900+ CS in 3 Promotion Tournament wins).
Hyper-aggressive carry who will rack up Kills against anyone. Has the raw mechanics to outplay anyone, but be wary of his Death totals.
Synergizes with Vasilii well and benefits off the strong team-fights LMQ possesses (34 Assists in 3 Promotion games).
Capable of delivering huge games when at his best (27.8 pts in wins). A new home in Dignitas should lead to more of those performances.
Can carry when needed (26.4 pts on average in CST's wins), and will have less pressure and more room to operate with Dignitas.
Top Korean Challenger player enters the Summer Split with high expectations; communication with other teammates will be key to success.
One of EU's top-ranked Challenger players, needs to establish synergy with veteran solo laners. Their experience should help him settle in.
NiQ is new to the LCS, but with Diamond ganking, his ceiling could be high. Be careful to keep an eye on others getting a try-out, though.
A veteran of competitive LoL who should be able to  transition into supporting of one EU's most promising carries in MrRalleZ.
Previously one of the top ADCs in the Challenger Series; must develop quickly, but can potentially make an immediate impact.
Mancloud has shown capacity to carry in the LCS, but will face a tough role coming in as a sub.
